### Transcendence
*18th-level monk feature* <br/>
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have transcended the limited connections between body and spirit. You can use your action to spend 4 ki points to partially shift your body into the spiritual realm, becoming invisible for 1 minute. During that time, you also have resistance to all damage but force damage.

Additionally, you can spend 8 ki points to enter a state of deep meditation, allowing your spirit to become untethered from your physical form. As an action, you can project your spirit from your body. The body you leave behind is unconscious and in a state of suspended animation.

Your spirit resembles your mortal form in almost every way, replicating game statistics but not your possessions. Any damage or other effects that apply to your spirit or physical body affects the other. Your spirit can remain outside your body for up to 1 hour or until your concentration is broken (as if concentrating on a spell). When your projection ends, your spirit returns to your body or your body magically teleports to your spirit’s space (your choice).

While projecting your spirit, your spirit and body gain resistance all damage but force damage. Additionally, you have a flying speed equal to your walking speed and can hover. You can move through creatures and objects as if they were difficult terrain, but you take 1d10 force damage if you end your turn inside a creature or an object.

### Grand Master
*20th-level monk feature* <br/>
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have achieved true mastery of your inner self. Your Wisdom and either your Dexterity or Strength scores increase by 4. Your maximum for those scores is now 24.

Additionally, if you start your turn with no chi points, you immediately regain 1 chi point.

## Swift Reflexes
### Deflect Blows
While you are not wearing medium or heavy armor or wielding a shield, you can use your reaction when you are hit by a weapon attack to deflect the blow. When you do so, the damage you take from the attack is reduced by 1d10 + your Dexterity + your monk level.

If the attack is from a melee weapon and you reduce the damage to 0, you can spend 1 chi point to make a melee attack with an unarmed strike or monk weapon against the attacker or against another target within reach of both you and the attacker. On a hit, you can push the target up to 5 feet away or knock it prone.

If the attack is from a ranged weapon and you reduce the damage to 0, you can catch the missile if it is small enough for you to hold in one hand and you have at least one hand free. If you catch a missile in this way, you can spend 1 chi point to make a ranged attack with the weapon or piece of ammunition you just caught, as part of the same reaction. You make this attack with proficiency, regardless of your weapon proficiencies, and the missile counts as a monk weapon for the attack, which has a normal range of 20 feet and a long range of 60 feet.

**[Separate?]**

### Leaping Evasion
*Prerequisite: 7th level*

When you succeed on a Dexterity save against a spell or effect that affects an area, you can use your reaction to attempt to jump out of the effect's area. This movement does not provoke attacks of opportunity.

**[Needs more cowbell.]**

