\pagebreak

### Way of the Evoker

#### Scaleclad Warrior
*3rd-level Way of the Evoker feature*<br/>
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You learn the Draconic language, if you did not know it already, and gain proficiency in medium armor. You continue to gain the benefits of your monk class features while wearing medium armor.

In addition you learn two cantrips of your choice: *control flames*, *gust*, *mold earth*, or *shape water*. Wisdom is your spellcasting modifier for these spells. You learn an additional cantrip from this list when you reach 6th and 10th level in this class.

#### Evocations
*3rd-level Way of the Evoker feature*<br/>
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You learn to use the power of chi to mimic the abilities of the dragonflights through evocations. An evocation requires you to spend chi points each time you use it.

**Evocations Known.** You know three evocations of your choice. You learn two additional disciplines of your choice at 6th, 10th and 17th level. Whenever you learn a new evocation, you can also replace one evocation that you already know with a different one.

**Essence Chi.** You gain an additional pool of chi points equal to half your monk level (rounded up). You can use either pool of chi points to cast your evocations but your essence chi points can not be used for any monk ability that isn't an evocation.

You regain all expended essence chi points when you finish a long rest.

**Casting Evocation Spells.** Some evocations allow you to cast spells. See chapter 10 of the Player's Handbook for the general rules of spellcasting. To cast one of these spells, you use its casting time and other rules, but you don't need to provide material components for it.

Once you reach 5th level in this class, you can spend additional chi points to increase the level of that spell, provided that the spell has an enhanced effect at a higher level, as *burning hands* does. The spell's level increases by 1 for each additional chi point you spend. For example, if you are a 5th-level monk and use **???Sweeping Cinder Strike???** to cast *burning hands*, you can spend 3 chi points to cast it as a 2nd-level spell (the evocation's base cost of 2 chi points plus 1).

The maximum number of chi points you can spend to cast a spell in this way (including its base chi point cost and any additional chi points you spend to increase its level) is determined by your monk level, as shown in the Spells and Chi Points table.

##### Spells and Chi Points
Monk Levels | Maximum Chi Points for a Spell
:----------:|:------------------------------:
5th-8th     | 3
9th-12th    | 4
13th-16th   | 5
17th-20th   | 6

